CSS button interview test
http://codepen.io/mobify/pen/GtqKj
/*
    
    INSTRUCTIONS

    Using CSS properties alone, recreate this button: 

        http://i.imgur.com/gnZnY.png. 

    Spend no longer than 15 minutes on it, we don't 
    expect it to be a perfect match. It's open book, 
    feel free to hit Google but be prepared to 
    explain your solution.

*/
a {
    margin: 20px;
    font-family: arial;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    display: inline-block;
    font: bold 150% sans-serif;
    text-decoration:none;
    text-align: center;
    border-radius: 5px;
    padding: 12px 24px;
    box-shadow: 0px 0px 4px #222, 0px 0px 0px 9px #CCC,0px 0px 0px 11px #FFF, 0px 0px 0px 13px #555, 0px 0px 2px 10px #777, 0px 0px 30px black;
    color:#333;
    background: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, color-stop(0%, #EEE), color-stop(100%, #999));
   }
 
 
a:before, a:after {
content: "\2605";
font-size: .75em; color: #777;
 
}
#Questions
- How to handle the multiple borders? With multiple box shadows.
- Text-transform Uppercase
- How to handle the stars? unicode and psuedo elements (before, after)
Psuedo elements in CSS not HTML to affect styling and not the content. Sometimes good to create new elements to hold styles. 
- Subtle text shadow under the letters. text-shadow: 0 .75px white
- Linear gradient or inset box shadow to split the background of the button
- Border radius nesting is not great. Give the box shadow a border radius.
- Be careful about nest border radius. 
- font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
- Curves on Helvetica are flat 
- curves on arial 

Blog:
- Write about how to approach this challenge, then how we will approach it next time.

